{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01F7z8WskuRuLBA9pAXNua9t","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to understand how Elasticsearch secure settings work. The Elasticsearch keystore is the proper place to store credentials (not elasticsearch.yml or env vars). The approach is:\n\n1. Create the `es-secure-settings` secret with the MinIO credentials in the format that Elasticsearch keystore expects\n2. Use `elasticsearch-keystore` to add the credentials to the keystore on each node\n3. Register the snapshot repository named \"minio-repo\"\n4. Create a snapshot\n\nThe task says \"Credentials are stored in the Secret 'es-secure-settings'\" but that secret doesn't exist yet. I need to create it.\nFor the S3-compatible MinIO integration, I need to set `s3.client.default.access_key` and `s3.client.default.secret_key` in the keystore. In Kubernetes, I can either create the secret with the keystore entries or use the keystore API to load them from a mounted file.\n\nThe challenge is that the keystore is per-node and needs to be populated before Elasticsearch starts. I'm considering an init container approach that mounts the secret and populates the keystore, or using the reload_secure_settings API after the keystore is already configured. I should also verify whether there's a minio service running and what the correct endpoint format would be for connecting to it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1263,"cache_read_input_tokens":31642,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1263},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae89d6f6-ac7a-49ae-94ca-dcf73a9f115a","uuid":"fd40a97a-95e3-4721-a7a6-82b709ee8b56","request_id":"req_011Ccex7rCsFMx8dWNgy